{"type":"assistant","message":{"model":"claude-sonnet-4-6","id":"msg_01NKwU1dzdCenRKqnTuS9gCM","type":"message","role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"Now I understand the logic. The key point: corroboration only runs in the `if (allCapsSelected.length >= 2)` path. So tests 1 and 2 need at least 2 ALL_CAPS candidates that survive earlier filtering.\n\nFor test 3 (single title), corroboration doesn't run at all because there's only one ALL_CAPS candidate.\n\nNow let me think about the mock embed functions for each test:\n\n**Test 1**: The input from the task description has:\n- \"DAT FLATBREADS\" - orphaned OCR artifact \n- \"FINNISH MILK FLATBREADS\" - real title #1\n\n\n- \"FINNISH POTATO FLATBREADS\" - real title #2\n\nFor the mock embed, I need all three to score as titles so I get 3 ALL_CAPS candidates in the selection pool, then corroboration will filter out \"DAT FLATBREADS\" since \"DAT\" doesn't appear in any other line. The corroboration check will fail for that one because it's isolated.\n\nNow looking at \"FINNISH MILK FLATBREADS\" - all three words are at least 3 letters, and each one appears elsewhere in the text: \"FINNISH\" shows up in another title, \"MILK\" is in the body text, and \"FLATBREADS\" appears across multiple lines. That gives it a perfect corroboration score of 1.0, which passes the threshold.\n\nFor \"FINNISH POTATO FLATBREADS\", the same logic applies - all three words clear the length requirement and each one gets corroborated from different parts of the content, hitting that 1.0 score needed to pass.\n\nSo for the test mock, I need to set up the titleWords to include all three of these phrases so they're recognized as titles from the start. The substring matching in the mock means if \"flatbreads\" is in titleWords, it'll match across all three variants.\n\nBut that creates a problem - body text like \"These traditional Finnish milk flatbreads are soft and delicious...\" would also get flagged as title-like, which could throw off the scoring. I need to be more precise and use the exact title phrases instead of just the common word. I see the issue now—using substring matching with case-insensitive comparison means body text containing \"finnish milk flatbreads\" would incorrectly be flagged as a title. I need to use the exact uppercased strings from the titles and match them case-insensitively, so only the actual title lines get marked as titles while descriptive text with the same words doesn't.\n\nLet me look at the test to understand the length constraints the algorithm applies to filter out candidates that are too long or short to be titles. The structural patterns should dominate here—ALL_CAPS lines like \"FINNISH MILK FLATBREADS\" and \"FINNISH POTATO FLATBREADS\" would naturally be identified as headings and win out over body text. I'll keep the titleWords simple with just those key phrases and trust the algorithm filters the body text correctly, then verify this works with the existing test pattern that checks corroboration filtering for \"DAT FLATBREADS\". I need to verify that all three candidates will actually make it through the filtering stages before corroboration can happen. \"DAT FLATBREADS\" should pass as an all-caps two-word phrase, and \"FINNISH MILK FLATBREADS\" should also survive as a three-word all-caps candidate, so both should end up in the pool for the corroboration step to filter appropriately. The lowercase line wouldn't qualify as an ALL_CAPS candidate. For the chicken soup and beef stew test, both titles have clear corroboration—their key words appear throughout the body text in ingredient lists and instructions. With the golonka test, there's only a single ALL_CAPS title so corroboration doesn't even run, and the Polish ingredient names don't contain the word \"golonka\" anyway.\n\nNow I need to write out the actual test cases. I'm creating a separate describe block for the corroboration behavior tests, and I'll use `extractTitleWithEmbeddings` since that's the function that actually handles the corroboration logic. The task mentions `extractTitle` but that's synchronous—the async version with embeddings is what I need here.\n\nWriting the test cases...","signature":""}],"stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":1,"cache_creation_input_tokens":1255,"cache_read_input_tokens":32374,"cache_creation":{"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":0,"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":1255},"output_tokens":8,"service_tier":"standard","inference_geo":"not_available"},"context_management":null},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"ae953361-806f-4043-a5a1-bef831914d71","uuid":"8c374528-baca-446f-b391-5a912b99f76b"}
