{"type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"tool_use_id":"toolu_01YAsq2tUUQXMnieJR4QpeJC","type":"tool_result","content":[{"type":"text","text":"Now I have everything I need. Here is the full review.\n\n---\n\n# Code Review: `describe(\"corroboration (multi-title filtering)\")` block\n\n## Review Metrics\n- Files Reviewed: 2\n- Critical Issues: 0\n- High Priority: 1\n- Medium Priority: 3\n- Suggestions: 2\n\n## Executive Summary\n\nThe three new tests are structurally sound and non-trivial — they cannot pass without the corroboration path actually running. However, the third test (\"does not apply corroboration to single-title pages\") has a flawed premise that makes it weaker than the comment claims. The `beforeEach` is redundant and signals a misunderstanding of the existing test structure. Two mock embed design decisions reduce confidence in what the tests actually prove.\n\n---\n\n## HIGH Priority\n\n### 1. Third test conflates \"corroboration does not fire\" with \"single title is returned correctly\"\n\n**File**: `/Users/eryk.napierala/Projects/fasola/lib/text-classifier/__tests__/title-extractor.test.ts:455`\n\n**Impact**: The test comment says \"Corroboration only runs when >= 2 ALL_CAPS candidates are selected\" and asserts `GOLONKA PIECZONA` is returned. This assertion would pass even if corroboration were accidentally applied to single titles and incorrectly filtered them — as long as the final output happened to still be that one title. The test cannot distinguish between \"corroboration was correctly skipped\" and \"corroboration ran and made no mistake.\"\n\n**Root Cause**: The intent is to guard against a regression where corroboration logic fires on a single candidate and wrongly suppresses it. But the production code gate is `allCapsSelected.length >= 2` (line 1287). To actually test that guard, you'd need a single ALL_CAPS title whose words do NOT appear in the document body, so that if corroboration ran it would fail and the title would be dropped. With the current input, every word of `GOLONKA PIECZONA` appears in the body (`golonka`, `pieczona` are not present as body words — but the corroboration threshold is 100% and the words aren't in the body lines, so if corroboration ran, the title would be eliminated). Actually, this is worth checking more carefully.\n\nLooking at `corroborationScore`: it uppercases the search (`allLines[i].toUpperCase().includes(word)`), and `word` comes from `candidateText.split(...).filter(w => w.replace(/[^a-zA-ZÀ-ÿ]/g, '').length >= 3)`. For `GOLONKA PIECZONA`, the words checked would be `GOLONKA` and `PIECZONA`. In the document body: `\"Składniki na 4 porcje\"`, `\"1 kg mięsa\"`, `\"2 cebule\"`, `\"3 ząbki czosnku\"`, `\"Mięso umyć i osuszyć\"`, `\"Cebulę pokroić w plastry\"`. None of these contain `GOLONKA` or `PIECZONA`. So if corroboration somehow ran on a single candidate, it would eliminate it and the test would catch the regression.\n\nThis means the test works, but its internal logic happens to be correct by accident rather than by design — the comment explanation is wrong. The test should clarify this and the word choices should be explicit about the vocabulary gap.\n\n**Solution**: Update the comment to accurately describe what makes the test effective:\n\n```typescript\nit(\"does not apply corroboration to single-title pages\", async () => {\n  // Corroboration gate: allCapsSelected.length >= 2 (production line 1287).\n  // This input has exactly one ALL_CAPS candidate. \"GOLONKA\" and \"PIECZONA\"\n  // do NOT appear in the body lines, so if corroboration incorrectly ran,\n  // it would eliminate the title and result would be undefined — failing the test.\n  // Passing confirms the >= 2 gate prevents premature filtering.\n  const embed = createMockEmbed([\"golonka pieczona\"], []);\n  ...\n```\n\n---\n\n## MEDIUM Priority\n\n### 2. `beforeEach(_resetEmbeddingCacheForTests)` is redundant\n\n**File**: `/Users/eryk.napierala/Projects/fasola/lib/text-classifier/__tests__/title-extractor.test.ts:383`\n\n**Impact**: The outer `describe(\"extractTitleWithEmbeddings\")` block already has `beforeEach(() => { _resetEmbeddingCacheForTests(); })` at line 91–93. Because `beforeEach` in Jest applies to all tests in the current describe scope and all nested describe scopes, any `beforeEach` registered in the parent block runs before every test in child blocks as well.\n\nThe inner `beforeEach` is therefore entirely redundant. It does not cause a double-invocation problem (resetting null to null is harmless), but it implies to the reader that the inner block is independent — that it does not benefit from the outer setup — which is misleading and could lead someone to remove the outer `beforeEach` thinking the inner one covers it.\n\n**However**: The new block is at the **same level** as `describe(\"extractTitleWithEmbeddings\")`, not nested inside it. Both are top-level describes. So the outer `beforeEach` does NOT apply here. The inner `beforeEach` is actually necessary.\n\nThis is an organizational smell: the corroboration tests are logically a subset of `extractTitleWithEmbeddings` tests (they all call `extractTitleWithEmbeddings`), but they live in a sibling describe rather than a nested one, forcing `_resetEmbeddingCacheForTests` to be re-declared. Either nesting the new block inside `extractTitleWithEmbeddings` would eliminate the duplication, or the `_resetEmbeddingCacheForTests` call should be moved to a top-level `beforeEach`.\n\n**Solution**: Nest the corroboration block inside `extractTitleWithEmbeddings`:\n\n```typescript\ndescribe(\"extractTitleWithEmbeddings\", () => {\n  beforeEach(() => {\n    _resetEmbeddingCacheForTests();\n  });\n\n  // ... existing tests ...\n\n  describe(\"corroboration (multi-title filtering)\", () => {\n    // No beforeEach needed — inherited from parent\n    it(\"rejects orphaned OCR artifact ...\", async () => { ... });\n    ...\n  });\n});\n```\n\n### 3. First test (orphan rejection) does not verify DAT is actually present in `selected` before corroboration runs\n\n**File**: `/Users/eryk.napierala/Projects/fasola/lib/text-classifier/__tests__/title-extractor.test.ts:386`\n\n**Impact**: The test correctly verifies the final output excludes `DAT FLATBREADS`. But it does not verify that `DAT FLATBREADS` was ever a candidate — if the pre-filtering or scoring steps happened to exclude it before corroboration, the test passes for the wrong reason. The embed mock lists `\"dat flatbreads\"` as a title word, which should give it a high title score, so it likely does become a candidate. But the surrounding lines (`\"2 cup plus 1 tablespoon...\"`, `\"nto a loured work counter...\"`) look like garbled OCR, and `isLikelyGarbled` could affect line processing in ways that might prevent `DAT FLATBREADS` from ever entering `allCapsSelected`.\n\n**Root Cause**: The test has rich realistic-looking OCR noise (misspellings, garbled tokens) at the top, which is good for simulating the real problem, but it makes it harder to reason about whether `DAT FLATBREADS` actually reaches the corroboration gate. The test is essentially an integration test for the whole pipeline, where the specific thing being tested (corroboration filtering) is several layers deep.\n\n**Suggestion**: A comment explaining why `DAT FLATBREADS` definitely becomes a candidate (or a simpler preamble that isolates the corroboration path) would increase confidence. Alternatively, the `corroborationScore` function is already exported — a dedicated unit test at that level would prove the filtering logic directly without depending on the full pipeline.\n\n### 4. Mock embed inputs for the second test do not stress the corroboration threshold\n\n**File**: `/Users/eryk.napierala/Projects/fasola/lib/text-classifier/__tests__/title-extractor.test.ts:427`\n\n**Impact**: The \"keeps legitimate multi-recipe titles\" test uses inputs where both titles' words (`chicken`, `soup`, `beef`, `stew`) appear abundantly in the body text, yielding a corroboration score of 1.0 for each. This tests the trivial \"everything passes\" path.\n\nThe more interesting boundary is the ≥67% threshold for candidates with more than 3 content words. No test exercises a candidate that passes at 67%+ but would fail at 100%. This means if someone accidentally changed `0.67` to `1.0` in the production code, no test would catch the regression for longer titles.\n\n**Solution**: Add a test with a 4+ word ALL_CAPS title where one content word is absent from the body (67% corroboration), confirming it still passes. Contrast with a companion case at 50% that gets filtered. These boundary cases are where the logic is most likely to regress.\n\n---\n\n## Suggestions\n\n### 5. The three tests could share a small helper for the common \"all-caps, no section headers\" embed pattern\n\nAll three corroboration tests call `createMockEmbed([...titles...], [])` with an empty `headerWords` array. A named constant or local alias would make the intent clearer without introducing complexity:\n\n```typescript\ndescribe(\"corroboration (multi-title filtering)\", () => {\n  // All corroboration tests use all-caps titles with no competing section headers.\n  // Pass [] for headerWords to keep section-header suppression out of the picture.\n  const noHeaders: string[] = [];\n  ...\n  const embed = createMockEmbed([\"dat flatbreads\", ...], noHeaders);\n```\n\nThis is minor, but the empty array at the call site currently requires the reader to check `createMockEmbed`'s signature to understand what it controls.\n\n### 6. `corroborationScore` is exported but has no direct unit tests\n\nThe function at `/Users/eryk.napierala/Projects/fasola/lib/text-classifier/title-extractor.ts:214` is independently testable and has precise numeric behavior (100% vs 67% thresholds, the `candidatePosition` exclusion). The three new tests exercise it indirectly through the full pipeline. A few direct tests for `corroborationScore` itself (e.g., \"returns 1.0 when all words appear in other lines\", \"returns 0.5 when one of two words is absent\", \"skips words shorter than 3 characters\", \"excludes the candidate line itself from search\") would create a more robust regression safety net and would be substantially simpler to write and maintain.\n\n---\n\n## Strengths\n\n- The OCR-realistic text in the first test (garbled prefix lines, blank line separators, realistic ingredient quantities) correctly simulates the real failure mode that motivated the feature.\n- The fallback guard on line 1306 (`corroboratedCaps.length >= 2 ? corroboratedCaps : allCapsSelected`) is exercised implicitly: the second test confirms that when both candidates pass, the result is exactly two titles, not a fallback to a single winner.\n- Naming is consistent with the rest of the file — test descriptions are statement-of-behavior style, matching the existing pattern."},{"type":"text","text":"agentId: aa3beb44e442ff1d9 (for resuming to continue this agent's work if needed)\n<usage>total_tokens: 28172\ntool_uses: 7\nduration_ms: 81950</usage>"}]}]},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"ae953361-806f-4043-a5a1-bef831914d71","uuid":"664fd6a8-6dac-4810-aa19-e4f249ab5a07","tool_use_result":{"status":"completed","prompt":"Review the test additions in `/Users/eryk.napierala/Projects/fasola/lib/text-classifier/__tests__/title-extractor.test.ts`.\n\nThe changes added a new `describe(\"corroboration (multi-title filtering)\")` block at the end of the file with 3 tests. The rest of the file was not changed.\n\nFocus on:\n1. Do the tests actually exercise the corroboration logic, or could they pass trivially?\n2. Is there duplicated setup/pattern that should be extracted?\n3. Are the mock embed inputs well-designed for the specific corroboration paths?\n4. Does the `beforeEach(_resetEmbeddingCacheForTests)` need to be in this block, or is it already covered by the outer describe block?\n5. Any inconsistencies with the existing test patterns in the same file?\n\nRead the full test file and the relevant corroboration code in the production file before reviewing.","agentId":"aa3beb44e442ff1d9","content":[{"type":"text","text":"Now I have everything I need. Here is the full review.\n\n---\n\n# Code Review: `describe(\"corroboration (multi-title filtering)\")` block\n\n## Review Metrics\n- Files Reviewed: 2\n- Critical Issues: 0\n- High Priority: 1\n- Medium Priority: 3\n- Suggestions: 2\n\n## Executive Summary\n\nThe three new tests are structurally sound and non-trivial — they cannot pass without the corroboration path actually running. However, the third test (\"does not apply corroboration to single-title pages\") has a flawed premise that makes it weaker than the comment claims. The `beforeEach` is redundant and signals a misunderstanding of the existing test structure. Two mock embed design decisions reduce confidence in what the tests actually prove.\n\n---\n\n## HIGH Priority\n\n### 1. Third test conflates \"corroboration does not fire\" with \"single title is returned correctly\"\n\n**File**: `/Users/eryk.napierala/Projects/fasola/lib/text-classifier/__tests__/title-extractor.test.ts:455`\n\n**Impact**: The test comment says \"Corroboration only runs when >= 2 ALL_CAPS candidates are selected\" and asserts `GOLONKA PIECZONA` is returned. This assertion would pass even if corroboration were accidentally applied to single titles and incorrectly filtered them — as long as the final output happened to still be that one title. The test cannot distinguish between \"corroboration was correctly skipped\" and \"corroboration ran and made no mistake.\"\n\n**Root Cause**: The intent is to guard against a regression where corroboration logic fires on a single candidate and wrongly suppresses it. But the production code gate is `allCapsSelected.length >= 2` (line 1287). To actually test that guard, you'd need a single ALL_CAPS title whose words do NOT appear in the document body, so that if corroboration ran it would fai